<h2>Link issues to WCAG criteria</h2>

<p>Linking accessibility issues to specific WCAG (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) criteria helps track compliance and ensures issues are properly categorised.</p>

<h3>What are WCAG criteria?</h3>
<p>WCAG criteria are specific, testable requirements that make content more accessible. They are organised by:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Level:</strong> A (minimum), AA (recommended), or AAA (enhanced)</li>
    <li><strong>Version:</strong> WCAG 2.0, 2.1, 2.2, etc.</li>
    <li><strong>Principle:</strong> Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, or Robust</li>
    <li><strong>Guideline:</strong> Specific area of accessibility</li>
</ul>

<h3>Linking criteria when creating an issue</h3>
<ol>
    <li>When creating a WCAG-type issue, you'll see a <strong>WCAG Criteria</strong> section</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Add WCAG Criterion</strong></li>
    <li>Search for or select the relevant WCAG criterion</li>
    <li>You can link multiple criteria to a single issue</li>
    <li>Selected criteria will appear in the issue details</li>
</ol>

<h3>Adding criteria to existing issues</h3>
<ol>
    <li>Navigate to the issue details page</li>
    <li>In the <strong>WCAG Criteria</strong> section, click <strong>Add Criterion</strong></li>
    <li>Search for the relevant criterion</li>
    <li>Select and save</li>
</ol>

<h3>WCAG criterion search</h3>
<p>The search allows you to find criteria by:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Criterion ID (e.g., "1.1.1", "2.4.1")</li>
    <li>Title or description keywords</li>
    <li>WCAG level (A, AA, AAA)</li>
    <li>WCAG version</li>
</ul>

<h3>Why link criteria?</h3>
<p>Linking issues to WCAG criteria provides:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Compliance tracking:</strong> See which criteria are failing</li>
    <li><strong>Reporting:</strong> Generate reports by WCAG criterion</li>
    <li><strong>Prioritisation:</strong> Focus on Level A and AA issues first</li>
    <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Clear record of what needs to be fixed</li>
    <li><strong>Statement generation:</strong> Criteria automatically included in statements</li>
</ul>

<h3>Viewing linked criteria</h3>
<p>On the issue details page, you can:</p>
<ul>
    <li>See all linked WCAG criteria</li>
    <li>View criterion details (level, version, description)</li>
    <li>Remove criteria if incorrectly linked</li>
    <li>See how many issues are linked to each criterion</li>
</ul>

<h3>Best practices</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Link issues to the most specific relevant criteria</li>
    <li>Link to all applicable criteria if an issue affects multiple</li>
    <li>Prioritise Level A and AA criteria</li>
    <li>Review linked criteria when updating issue status</li>
    <li>Use criteria links to identify patterns in accessibility issues</li>
</ul>

